racter that witnesses and litigants put forth in court. She not only reveals the role of law in constructing "race" but also offers a portrait of the culture of slavery, one that addresses historical debates about law, honor, and commerce in the American South.Gross maintains that witnesses and litigants drew on narratives available in the culture at large to explain the nature and origins of slaves' character, such as why slaves became runaways. But the legal process also shaped their expressions of racial ideology by favoring certain explanations over others. Double Character brings to life the law as a dramatic ritual in people's daily lives, looking at trials from the perspective of litigants, lawyers, doctors, and the slaves themselves. The author's approach combines the methods of cultural anthropology, quantitative social history, and critical race theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCourtszSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationzSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxLegal status, laws, etczSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxLegal status, laws, etc.zSouthern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAdeline.  aAfrican codes of honor.  aAndrews, Philo.  aBall, Charles.  aBrown, Andrew.  aCartwright, Samuel.  aCivil War colored regiments.  aCozzins v. Whitacker.  aDangerfield, Elizabeth.  aEmancipation Proclamation.  aForks-of-the-Road slave market.  aFreedmen's Bureau.  aGenovese, Eugene.  aGilbert.  aHagan v. Rist.  aHenderson, Charles.  aJohnson, William.  aKemble, Fanny.  aKyle, Christopher.  aLafortune.  aLinden (Natchez estate).  aLynch, Charles.  aMcKowen, Alexander.  aMelrose (Natchez estate).  aMinute books (Adams Circuit Court).  aNorthern 